YouTube Recommendations: What the Algorithm really shows us

Introduction: The Great YouTube Algorithm Mystery

Have you ever wondered if YouTube knows you a little too well? Or maybe youve even questioned whether those supposedly random recommendations are actually random at all? This data story explores what happens to YouTube recommendations when users are logged in versus when theyre browsing anonymously.

Through an observational study of 42 YouTube users homepage recommendations, we dive into the patterns, peculiarities, and potential biases of one of the worlds most influential recommendation algorithms. Fair warning: this sample size is much too small to derive any definitive conclusions, but the insights are surprisingly telling!

The Registration Reality Check

Plot 1: Boxplot showing YouTube recommendation unusualness ratings by login status. Logged-in users cluster around higher unusualness ratings, while anonymous users show a wider range with lower median.

Heres where things get interesting - when we look at how unusual people find their recommendations, logged-in and anonymous users tell completely different stories.

Anonymous users experience the full spectrum of surprise - from that seems pretty normal (rating 1) to where on Earth did that come from? (rating 5). Its as if the YouTube algorithm is throwing darts at a board when youre not logged in.

Meanwhile, logged-in users cluster around rating 4, suggesting their recommendations consistently surprise them in some way. The median tells the story: logged-in users typically rate unusualness as 4, while anonymous users sit at a very predictable 1. Perhaps knowing your viewing history makes YouTube more experimental?

The lower quartile comparison is particularly revealing - anonymous users bottom out at 1 (completely expected content), while logged-in users start at 2. This suggests that when YouTube doesnt know who you are, it plays it safe with trending, mainstream content that most people would find familiar.

What Types of Content Are We Seeing?

Plot 2: Stacked bar chart showing types of recommended content by login status. Logged-in users receive a mix of history-aligned, unfamiliar, and unexpected content. Anonymous users are mostly shown general interest and trending content.

The content breakdown reveals YouTubes two distinct personalities. For logged-in users, its a mixed bag:

  • 33% aligned with viewing history (no surprises there)
  • 22% featuring unfamiliar channels (YouTubes attempt to broaden horizons?)
  • 17% each for unexpected genres and content different from usual history

For anonymous users, its a different algorithm entirely:

  • 29% general interest content (safe, broad appeal)
  • 26% trending content (whats popular right now)
  • Only 14% each for truly random content or other categories

This suggests that YouTubes algorithm tends to default to the greatest hits approach when it doesnt know you - displaying a steady assortment of trending and broadly appealing content rather than taking risks with anything too controversial or polarizing.

The Time Factor: When Do We Browse?

Plot 3: Bar chart showing frequency of YouTube usage by time of day and login status. Most logged-in users browse at night; anonymous users are more active in the afternoon.

Our browsing patterns reveal that were night owls! Most observations from this sample happened during nightly hours (8PM-6AM), with 15 logged-in users and 2 anonymous users active during these hours.

Interestingly, no one in our sample browsed during evening hours (6PM-8PM) - perhaps everyones too busy with dinner or commuting? The afternoon sees the most balanced split between logged-in and anonymous users (9 vs 10), while mornings heavily favour logged-in users (5 vs 1).

This timing data, while limited by our small sample, hints at when different types of users engage with YouTube. Night browsing is dominated by logged-in users who might be winding down with content tailored to their interests, while daytime browsing shows more anonymous exploration.

The Reality Check: What We Can (and Cant) Conclude

Lets be honest - with 42 responses (29 logged-in, 13 anonymous), were barely scratching the surface of the logistics behind YouTubes recommendation algorithm system. The skewed sample toward logged-in users particularly limits our ability to draw strong conclusions about anonymous browsing patterns.

However, some patterns emerge clearly enough to be noteworthy:

  1. YouTubes algorithm behaves fundamentally differently based on login status
  2. Anonymous users receive more predictable, mainstream content
  3. Logged-in users get a more diverse (and often surprising) mix of recommendations
  4. Browsing patterns vary significantly by time of day

While these findings align with what we might expect from a personalisation algorithm, they raise intriguing questions: Is YouTubes personalised approach actually more surprising than its anonymous default? And what does this mean for how we discover new content online?

Final Thoughts: The Algorithms Dual Nature

This small glimpse into YouTubes recommendation system reveals its dual nature - conservative when it doesnt know you, adventurous when it does. Whether this is by design or emergent behaviour remains an open question.

Perhaps the most telling finding is that knowing your data leads to more unexpected recommendations, not fewer. In trying to personalise our experience, YouTube might actually be making it more unpredictable. Whether thats a bug or a feature depends on what were looking for when we open that app at 1 AM.

The algorithm remains a mystery, but at least now we have a tiny window into its logic.
